  "prompt": "LIGO uses laser light, but why are the lasers not altered by the gravitational waves?",
  "response": "Great question! There are several important points to understand about how LIGO's lasers interact with gravitational waves:\n\n1. Laser Beam Length:\n- Gravitational waves cause extremely tiny changes in distance (typically much smaller than a proton's width)\n- These minute changes are what LIGO is designed to detect by measuring laser interference patterns\n\n2. Laser Properties:\n- The laser itself is not fundamentally altered by gravitational waves\n- Gravitational waves affect spacetime geometry, which changes the physical distance between mirrors\n- This distance change is what causes interference in the laser's path\n\n3. Measurement Technique:\n- LIGO uses laser interferometry\n- Laser beams are split and bounce between precisely positioned mirrors\n- When a gravitational wave passes, it slightly stretches and compresses these distances\n- This causes a detectable change in the interference pattern of the laser beams\n\n4. Precision Measurement:\n- LIGO can detect distance changes as small as 1/10,000th the width of a proton\n- This extreme sensitivity allows detection of gravitational wave effects\n\n5. Laser Characteristics:\n- The laser's wavelength and coherence remain essentially unchanged\n- Only the path length is affected by gravitational wave distortions\n\nThe laser itself remains fundamentally unaltered; it's the spacetime geometry that changes.",
